FILL_CH5 = {
  "5": {
    "2": "<p>The community's boastful tolerance of the incest case (<em>pephysiomenoi este</em>, you are puffed up) reflects the Corinthians' valuation of <em>sophrosyne</em> in the sense of self-mastery, not communal moral accountability. In Greco-Roman voluntary associations (<em>collegia</em>), internal discipline over members' private sexual conduct was generally not practiced — associations were social-network organizations, not moral communities. The Corinthians may be applying this association-model to the church, treating personal sexual conduct as outside communal jurisdiction.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Paul's judicial action 'in spirit' while 'absent in body' invokes the concept of legal representation by letter, known in Greco-Roman practice — the absent party could authorize action through written mandate. The apostle acting through his written authority is analogous to the Roman legal concept of the <em>mandatum</em> (power of attorney). Paul's 'already judged' (<em>kekrika</em>, perfect tense) indicates a decision made and communicated through correspondence, a recognized form of formal judgment in the ancient world.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The assembly convened 'in the name of the Lord Jesus' with Paul's spirit present — the gathering language echoes Jewish community deliberation. In Second Temple Judaism, communal courts (<em>beit din</em>) convened to rule on cases of communal discipline; the Qumran community had elaborate rules for expulsion from the yahad (1QS 6-7). Paul's procedure here is analogous: a formal communal assembly pronounces a judicial verdict in the presence of divine authority, following recognizable patterns of Jewish communal jurisdiction adapted for the Gentile church.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The expulsion formula 'deliver to Satan for the destruction of the flesh' has parallels in both Jewish and Hellenistic contexts. In the Dead Sea Scrolls (1QS 2:5-9), the community's curse-formula devoted the wicked to Satan's dominion outside the covenant community. In Greco-Roman associations, expulsion (<em>ekklēsia</em> vote) placed the offender back in the social sphere dominated by honor-competition and spiritual peril. The formula assumes Satan's domain is outside the protected community — expulsion removes the offender from the church's zone of covenantal protection, a disciplinary measure meant to produce repentance, not final destruction.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The leaven metaphor ('a little leaven leavens the whole lump') was a common ancient proverb for the spread of corrupting influence. In Second Temple Judaism, leaven was associated with moral impurity — the Passover purge of leaven (Exod 12:15-20) was ritually and metaphorically loaded. The Essenes regarded moral impurity as contagious within the community. Paul applies this Jewish purity logic to the Corinthian community's tolerance of the incest case: the community's corporate holiness is compromised by the uncorrected impurity within it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Paul's Passover typology ('Christ our Passover has been sacrificed') draws on the foundational Jewish festival commemorating the Exodus from Egypt. The Passover lamb (Exod 12:1-13) was sacrificed to protect Israel from the destroying angel. The metaphorical application was established in Second Temple Judaism: the Passover was interpreted as the prototype of God's eschatological redemption (Isa 43:16-19; 52:11-12). Paul's identification of Christ as the Passover lamb (not simply a Passover analogy) grounds the ethical imperative in the festival's temporal structure: the sacrifice has happened, now the festival of unleavened bread must begin.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The 'festival' (<em>heortazomen</em>, let us celebrate) picks up the Passover-festival metaphor: the sacrifice of the lamb was followed by the week-long festival of unleavened bread (Exod 12:15-20; 13:6-7), during which all leaven was purged from the household and only unleavened bread was eaten. The Jewish household examination for leaven (<em>bedikat chametz</em>) before Passover was a formal religious duty. Paul translates this domestic purity rite into the community's expulsion of the sexually immoral member: the community is the Passover household that must be purged of its leaven before the festival can begin.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Paul references a prior letter ('I wrote to you in my letter') — a now-lost Pauline correspondence ('1 Corinthians' is actually the second extant letter). The Corinthians had apparently misunderstood the prior letter's injunction to avoid the immoral: they thought it meant avoiding all immoral people in the world, not only immoral members within the community. This misunderstanding reveals the practical challenge of Paul's community-ethics: the church existed in a pagan social environment where avoiding all contact with immoral people would require social withdrawal impossible in a Roman city.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Corinthians' social world — the <em>kosmos</em> (world) Paul references — was densely populated with the behaviors he lists: <em>pornoi</em> (sexually immoral), <em>pleonektai</em> (greedy), <em>harpages</em> (swindlers), <em>eidōlolatrēs</em> (idolaters). Commercial Corinth, with its two harbors and cosmopolitan population, had an especially active economy of vice. Prostitution (<em>porneia</em>) was widespread and legally unregulated; commercial exploitation (<em>pleonexia</em>) was endemic in the Mediterranean trading economy. Complete social separation from such a world was not practicable.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The vice list for community discipline (v. 11) includes both sexual and financial offenses, along with religious ones (idolater) and social ones (reviler, drunkard). The prohibition of table fellowship (<em>synesthiein</em>, eating together) was the most socially significant sanction available in the ancient world: meals were the primary social bonding mechanism, and exclusion from the common table was exclusion from the community's social existence. Jewish communities practiced table-separation to maintain purity; Paul applies this socially powerful tool to communal discipline.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Paul's distinction between judging insiders and outsiders (<em>tous exō / tous esō</em>) reflects the self-governance principle of the ancient association: the <em>thiasos</em> or <em>collegium</em> governed its own members' conduct but did not claim jurisdiction over non-members. Jewish communities similarly maintained internal courts (<em>beit din</em>) with jurisdiction over community members while recognizing Roman courts' jurisdiction over external matters. Paul invokes this principle: the church's communal discipline is legitimate within its own community; it has no mandate to police the wider world, whose judgment belongs to God.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The expulsion command ('purge the evil person from among you') cites Deuteronomy's communal-purification formula (Deut 17:7; 19:19; 22:21; 24:7) — each occurrence concerns a serious communal transgression requiring the community's purging to maintain its covenant status. Paul's use of Deuteronomic expulsion language signals that he regards the church as a covenant community with obligations analogous to those of Israel under the Torah. The community's holiness is not merely individual but corporate: the presence of unrepentant sin threatens the community's covenant integrity as a whole.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH6 = {
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The lawsuit problem: in Roman Corinth, the civil court system (<em>iudicia publica</em>) was the standard venue for resolving disputes between private citizens. The Corinthian community apparently used these courts to settle disputes between members. Paul characterizes the judges as <em>adikoi</em> (unrighteous/unjust) — using the same term that will appear in the vice list of vv. 9-10. The irony: the Corinthians are taking matters before judges whom Paul characterizes by the very vices being judged.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The eschatological role of the saints in judging the world and angels was a standard Second Temple Jewish expectation. The Qumran community expected to participate in God's final judgment (1QpHab 5:4; 4Q177); Wisdom of Solomon 3:8 declares the righteous will 'govern nations and rule over peoples.' Paul invokes this eschatological judicial role to argue by contrast: if believers are destined to judge the cosmos, how absurd that they cannot handle trivial commercial disputes within the community without appealing to pagan courts.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The judgment of angels adds a further eschatological dimension. In Second Temple Judaism, fallen angels were subject to final judgment (1 Enoch 10; 91:15; Jude 6) — and the righteous would participate in or witness this judgment. The reference here is not to the service of guardian angels but to the judgment of rebellious spiritual powers. Paul's logic is a fortiori: if believers will judge cosmic powers, surely they can judge <em>biōtika</em> (matters of everyday life) — a term implying the mundane and trivial compared to the cosmic.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The ironic recommendation to appoint the 'least esteemed' (<em>exouthenēmenoi</em>) as arbiters is a pointed social reversal. In Corinthian social culture, the most esteemed persons — those of high social standing, education, and rhetorical ability — were the expected arbiters of disputes. Paul inverts the honor hierarchy: if the Corinthians must have arbiters, why not use those the world regards as of no account? The reversal echoes the cross-wisdom of ch. 1-2: God uses the foolish and weak to shame the wise and strong.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The shame-appeal ('is there not a wise person among you?') deploys Corinthian social values against their behavior. The Corinthians prized <em>sophia</em> (wisdom) and <em>gnōsis</em> (knowledge) as markers of spiritual status. To lack a person wise enough to arbitrate between brothers is a profound failure by the community's own standards. Paul's irony is pointed: the community that boasts of its wisdom cannot handle a civil dispute without recourse to pagan judges.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Brother suing brother <em>epi apistōn</em> (before unbelievers) — the phrase's shaming force depends on the social context where communal disputes before outsiders advertised internal division. In both Jewish communities (Josephus, Against Apion 2.193-194) and Greco-Roman associations, internal dispute resolution was expected precisely to avoid the public shame of airing community conflicts before outsiders. Paul's rebuke operates entirely within this social logic: the Corinthians' resort to public courts is a communal shaming act, regardless of who wins.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Paul's recommendation — 'why not rather suffer wrong? why not rather be defrauded?' — draws on a philosophical tradition of equanimity under injustice. The Stoics (Epictetus, Discourses 4.5) and Cynics celebrated the ability to absorb insult and injustice without retaliation as a mark of genuine freedom. More directly, Jesus's teaching (Matt 5:39-40; Luke 6:29-30) forms the background: the willingness to absorb loss rather than seek legal redress was a mark of the community's distinctive ethos in contrast to honor-competition culture.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The accusation that Corinthians are themselves wronging and defrauding (<em>adikeite kai apostereite</em>) — not just being wronged — indicts both plaintiffs and defendants in the lawsuit culture. Commercial fraud and sharp practice (<em>pleonexia</em>) were pervasive in Corinthian trade; the archaeological record of Corinth as a major commercial hub (pottery, bronze, textiles, harbor fees) gives material texture to Paul's concern. The community is reproducing the commercial ethics of the marketplace rather than the counter-cultural economics of the Sermon on the Mount.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The vice list in vv. 9-10 contains two terms related to same-sex conduct: <em>malakoi</em> (soft, effeminate — men who took the passive role in male-male intercourse) and <em>arsenokoitai</em> (males who lie with males — Paul's compound drawn from the LXX of Lev 18:22 and 20:13). In the Roman context, male-male sexual activity was widespread and legally unregulated, but the active/passive distinction was socially loaded: free male citizens were expected to be active, not passive (<em>malakos</em> status was shameful). Paul's condemnation covers both roles without the Roman active/passive moral distinction — both exclude from the kingdom.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The full vice list — sexually immoral, idolaters, adulterers, soft (<em>malakoi</em>), males-lying-with-males, thieves, greedy, drunkards, revilers, swindlers — maps onto the social vices of commercial Corinth. The <em>pleonektai</em> (greedy/covetous) and <em>harpakes</em> (swindlers/extortioners) are commercial terms that speak directly to the marketplace behavior Paul criticized in v. 8. The <em>loidoroi</em> (revilers) are relevant to the honor-competition culture of the Corinthian elite where verbal attacks on rivals were a normal form of social competition. The list is not abstract but addresses recognizable Corinthian social vices.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The three-fold transformation formula — washed, sanctified, justified (<em>apeloysasthe, hēgiasthēte, edikaioōthēte</em>) — describes the social transition from pagan community membership to the church community. The 'washing' likely refers to baptism, which in the ancient world had a strong social-initiation dimension (cf. proselyte baptism in Second Temple Judaism; ritual washing at Qumran for community entry). The transition was marked by a comprehensive change of social identity: the former vices belonged to the former community membership; the new community membership comes with a new social identity defined by the Spirit and Christ's name.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The body-for-food / food-for-body slogan ('food is meant for the stomach and the stomach for food') is a Corinthian philosophical axiom about bodily appetites as morally neutral. The Stoics and Epicureans both held versions of the view that bodily appetites (food, sex) were natural and should be managed rationally but were not inherently moral. The Corinthian 'pneumatics' apparently extended this to sexual conduct: as the body will be destroyed, what one does with it is morally inconsequential. Paul's counter-argument shifts the framework entirely: the body is for the Lord, not for immorality, and God will raise it.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Paul grounds the body's moral significance in resurrection. In the Greco-Roman context, the body (<em>sōma</em>) was generally regarded as the soul's temporary vehicle, destined for dissolution — hence the indifference to what one did with it. Paul's resurrection-body theology (developed fully in ch. 15) directly refutes this: God, who raised the Lord, will also raise us. The body's eschatological future determines its present moral status. This was not an argument available in any form of Greek philosophy; it is Paul's characteristically Jewish-Christian innovation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The 'members of Christ' (<em>melē Christou</em>) language is ecclesiological: the individual body participates in the corporate body of Christ (12:12-27). The horror of making Christ's members into members of a prostitute (<em>pornē</em>) is not merely personal moral failure but a violation of the corporate Christological identity. Prostitution (<em>porneia</em>) in Roman Corinth was commercial, legal, and socially embedded: there were brothels near the agora, and <em>hetairai</em> (educated courtesans) were fixtures of elite male social life. What Paul calls a violation of Christ's body was, to Corinthian social culture, an unremarkable commercial transaction.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Paul cites Gen 2:24 ('the two will become one flesh') to argue that sexual union creates a covenantal bond — not merely a transactional bodily contact. In Jewish exegesis, Gen 2:24 was foundational for marriage law: the rabbis used it to define the marriage union (m. Ketubbot 1:1). By citing it for the union with a prostitute, Paul argues that even a commercial sexual transaction creates a real (if illicit) covenantal bond of the 'one flesh' type. This significantly raises the moral stakes: fornication is not a trivial bodily transaction but a covenantal act with spiritual consequences.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The contrast between being 'one flesh' with a prostitute and 'one spirit' with the Lord draws on the Jewish concept of covenant union. In Second Temple Judaism, Israel's covenant relationship with YHWH was described in marital terms (Hosea 2; Ezekiel 16; Song of Songs in its allegorical reading). The 'one spirit' union with the Lord is the positive counterpart to the 'one flesh' bond of sexual union: both are real, both are exclusive, and both are violated by sexual immorality. The spiritual union with Christ is the prior commitment that sexual immorality betrays.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The command to 'flee sexual immorality' (<em>pheugete tēn porneian</em>) uses the language of flight common in Jewish moral exhortation. The Joseph story (Gen 39:12 — Joseph fleeing Potiphar's wife) was a standard example in Jewish moral instruction (T. Joseph 9:3; Philo, On Joseph 40-43). The Joseph narrative was frequently invoked in Second Temple Judaism as the model of sexual self-control in a pagan environment — precisely the situation facing Corinthian Christians in a city saturated with commercial prostitution. Flight, not negotiation, is the response to sexual temptation in this tradition.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The commercial metaphor of purchase (<em>ēgoriasthēte timēs</em>, you were bought at a price) reflects the Greco-Roman institution of slavery and manumission. Slaves could be bought and freed, but freedom came at a price — either paid by the slave (from savings) or by a patron. Paul's use of redemption-purchase language places believers as those who have been bought by Christ: they belong to him as purchased property, their freedom is freedom-within-ownership. The obligation to 'glorify God in your body' follows from this ownership-transfer: the body that has been purchased belongs to its new owner and must serve his purposes, not the former owner's.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH7 = {
  "7": {
    "2": "<p>The recommendation of marriage 'because of sexual immoralities' (<em>dia de tas porneias</em>) situates marriage within a specific social problem. Commercial prostitution (<em>porneia</em>) was ubiquitous in Roman Corinth. Paul's social-practical argument: marriage provides a licit sexual outlet that prevents recourse to prostitution. This is not Paul's full theology of marriage (Eph 5:25-32 goes much further) but a pragmatic argument for the Corinthian context. Roman marriage law under Augustus's Lex Iulia (18 BCE) similarly encouraged marriage and penalized sexual irregularity among the citizen class.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The 'conjugal duty' (<em>opheilomenēn eunoian</em>) reflects the mutual obligations of the Roman marriage contract. Roman law recognized that both husband and wife had obligations within marriage, and withholding marital rights could be grounds for complaint. Paul frames the marital sexual obligation in terms of mutual debt — a more egalitarian formulation than the Roman legal default, which gave greater juridical power to the husband. The parity of obligation (v. 3-4) is notable in a culture that generally treated marital sexuality from the husband's perspective.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The mutual-authority claim ('the wife does not have authority over her own body, but the husband does; likewise the husband does not have authority over his own body, but the wife does') is remarkable by Roman standards. Roman law gave the husband (<em>paterfamilias</em>) considerable authority over the household's members. Paul's reciprocal formulation — the wife has authority over the husband's body as much as he has authority over hers — distributes bodily authority symmetrically in a cultural context where it was distributed asymmetrically. This mutual ownership within marriage is Paul's practical application of the 'one flesh' principle of Gen 2:24.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The agreement for temporary abstinence 'for prayer' (<em>proseuche</em>) has parallels in Jewish sexual-purity regulations. The Qumran community required sexual abstinence before cultic activities (11QTemple 45:11-12); the Damascus Document prescribed similar requirements. The rabbinic tradition similarly recognized periods of conjugal abstinence for religious purposes. Paul's permission for temporary abstinence by mutual consent ('by agreement') is more permissive than some Jewish practices (the rabbis debated required conjugal frequency in m. Ketubbot 5:6), but the principle of religious purpose for abstinence is consistent with Second Temple Jewish practice.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Paul's 'by way of concession' (<em>kata syngnōmēn</em>) distinguishes what he permits from what he commands. In ancient rhetorical convention, the speaker distinguished between <em>boulēma</em> (what one desires/commands) and <em>syngnōmē</em> (concession, accommodation). Paul is making a pastoral accommodation to the reality of human sexual need while maintaining his preference for the undivided devotion of celibacy. This permission-not-command distinction was important for his argument that celibacy is a genuine charism, not a universal requirement — both states are legitimate.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Paul's statement 'I wish that all were as I am' identifies him as celibate, consistent with what we know about apostolic travel: the strenuous itinerant life of the first missionaries was easier to sustain without a family. Peter (mentioned in 9:5 as taking a wife) and the brothers of the Lord traveled with wives. The charism (<em>charisma</em>) of celibacy as a gift from God reflects the broader gift-theology of 1 Cor 12: celibacy is not a universal obligation but a specific endowment for those so called, analogous to other spiritual gifts.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The category 'unmarried' (<em>agamoi</em>) and 'widows' (<em>chērai</em>) in Paul's address covers a significant population in the Corinthian church. Roman widows of the propertied class were legally pressured to remarry under Augustus's legislation (the <em>Lex Papia Poppaea</em>, 9 CE penalized women without children who were not married within a certain age). Paul's contrary recommendation — that widows remain unmarried if they can — directly countered Roman social and legal pressure. The 'good' (<em>kalon</em>) of remaining unmarried is a counter-cultural stance within the Roman social framework.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The 'burning with passion' (<em>pyrouesthai</em>) that Paul mentions as the reason for marriage reflects ancient medical and philosophical thinking about sexual desire as an internal heat requiring outlet or control. The Stoic tradition spoke of passion (<em>pathos</em>) as a form of excessive heat that disturbed rational equanimity. Paul does not deny the reality of sexual desire but refuses the Stoic ideal of passion-elimination in favor of the Jewish realism of channeling desire into marriage. The pragmatic realism here is Pauline, not Stoic.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The distinction between 'not I but the Lord' (v. 10) and 'I, not the Lord' (v. 12) reflects Paul's awareness of a body of Jesus tradition — sayings of Jesus known to the community. Jesus's teaching on divorce (Mark 10:2-12; Luke 16:18) was known and binding on the community as a dominical command. Paul preserves the distinction between dominical authority and apostolic counsel — a methodologically important hermeneutical move that respects the chain of tradition while also claiming pastoral authority for his own judgments.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Separation without remarriage (<em>menetō agamos ē tō andri katallagētō</em>, let her remain unmarried or be reconciled to her husband) reflects the practical reality that some Corinthian marriages had broken down under the stress of the community's contested sexual ethics — some members may have withdrawn from conjugal life entirely in an overrealized eschatological asceticism. Paul's response: if separation has occurred, remarriage is not permitted (the Lord's command) and reconciliation is preferred. The option of permanent celibate separation is acknowledged but framed as second-best.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The 'mixed marriage' scenario — one believing spouse, one not — reflects the social reality of conversions in a pagan city. When one member of an established Roman household converted to Christianity, the household was divided. Roman marriage law gave some formal recognition to the wife's religion in certain contexts, but the paterfamilias's religious authority over the household (<em>ius religionis</em>) was significant. Paul's ruling that the believer should not divorce an unbelieving willing spouse is practically important: mass divorce of non-Christian spouses would have been socially disruptive and potentially dangerous.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The wife's right to remain in a mixed marriage is stated symmetrically with the husband's (vv. 12-13), again reflecting Paul's egalitarian marital framework. In Roman law, either spouse could dissolve the marriage by simply departing (<em>divortium</em>). The Christian restriction — do not divorce the consenting non-Christian spouse — applies equally to both the husband who is a believer and the wife who is a believer. The social implications were significant: Christian women in mixed marriages retained their marriages even against cultural pressure to conform to the husband's religion.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The 'sanctification' of the unbelieving spouse through the believing partner reflects an extension of Israel's purity-contagion logic into the Christian household. In Jewish purity law, holy objects and persons could transmit holiness by contact (Exod 29:37; Lev 6:27); Paul argues that the believing spouse's covenant holiness extends over the household rather than the unbelieving spouse's impurity contaminating the believer. The household (<em>oikos</em>) is the unit of social-religious life in the ancient world: what one member's status is affects the whole household's religious status.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The 'peace' (<em>eirēnē</em>) to which God has called the believer — invoked when the unbelieving spouse departs — reflects both the Jewish concept of <em>shalom</em> (comprehensive well-being) and the Roman <em>pax</em> (civic order). The permission for the believer to let the departing unbeliever go is a pastoral concession to the social reality of forced divorce: the abandoned Christian spouse is not bound to pursue the non-consenting pagan. The freedom here is the freedom from the obligation to preserve a marriage the other party has already ended.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The rhetorical question 'how do you know whether you will save your husband/wife?' acknowledges the missional possibility of conversion through the marriage relationship without making it a certainty. In Second Temple Jewish tradition, the pious household was seen as a sphere of potential influence on the non-pious (Tob 1:8; 14:9). Paul neither commands the believer to stay in hopes of converting the spouse, nor commands leaving. He acknowledges both the possibility of salvation and the uncertainty of its outcome — a realistic pastoral stance.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The 'calling' (<em>klēsis</em>) in which each person was called by God becomes the theological principle for the whole of ch. 7: social circumstances at conversion (married/unmarried, circumcised/uncircumcised, enslaved/free) are not to be immediately reversed by conversion. This 'remain as you are' principle had important social implications: Jewish Christians need not abandon Jewish identity; enslaved Christians need not seek immediate manumission; married people need not separate. The principle prevents the Christian community from becoming a social-disruption movement requiring radical severance from all pre-conversion commitments.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The circumcision/uncircumcision case illustrates the 'remain as you are' principle. <em>Epispasmos</em> (foreskin restoration) was a known Hellenistic practice: Jews who wanted to participate in Greek athletic nudity (in the gymnasium) could undergo a procedure to restore the foreskin's appearance (1 Maccabees 1:15; Josephus, Antiquities 12.241). Paul prohibits this procedure for Jewish Christians: the social desire to 'un-Jew' oneself for social acceptance is not a Christian value, any more than Gentile Christians should be required to be circumcised. Both ethnic markers are spiritually irrelevant.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The bracketing of circumcision and uncircumcision as 'nothing' (<em>ouden estin</em>) in favor of 'keeping God's commandments' reflects Paul's characteristic move in Galatians and Romans: the Torah's ceremonial markers do not constitute the community of God's people; covenant faithfulness does. What counts is not ethnic identity markers but faithfulness to the moral requirements of the covenant. This is thoroughly Jewish in its values (the prophets also relativized ritual vs. moral obedience, Mic 6:8; Amos 5:21-24) while being Christologically radicalized in its application.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The 'calling' (<em>klēsis</em>) in which each person was called — the governing principle restated. In ancient social analysis, <em>klēsis</em> had a philosophical dimension: Stoics counseled acceptance of one's assigned social position as the ordering of divine providence (Marcus Aurelius, Meditations 6.2). Paul's use of calling-language is analogous but reframed: the social circumstance is not merely philosophically accepted but is the specific context in which God's call has reached the person, and it remains the context for living out that call. Conversion does not erase or cancel prior social bonds and obligations.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The slavery case is the most socially charged application of the 'remain as you are' principle. In Roman Corinth, slavery was ubiquitous — estimates put the enslaved population at 25-35% of the Roman empire's total population. Corinth as a commercial hub had significant enslaved labor. The ambiguity of Paul's instruction ('but if you can gain your freedom, use it' — does <em>chrēsai</em> refer to using freedom or using the slave status?) has generated enormous debate. Most scholars now read it as permission or encouragement to take freedom if available, while the basic principle remains: God's call reaches enslaved persons where they are without requiring prior manumission.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The paradoxical formulation — the enslaved believer is the Lord's freed person, the free believer is Christ's slave — reflects Paul's creative reuse of manumission language. In Greco-Roman practice, the freed person (<em>libertus</em>) became a client of the former owner and owed ongoing obligations. Paul's 'freed person of the Lord' inverts this: the one whom the Lord has freed (from sin, from the law's condemnation) is genuinely free regardless of social status. The 'free' person who belongs to Christ as his slave has the highest possible owner: the exchange of human freedom for divine ownership is the ultimate upgrade.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The 'bought at a price' formula (echoing 6:20) frames the slave-freedom paradox theologically: the price paid is Christ's sacrificial death, which transfers ownership of every believer to Christ. The command 'do not become slaves of human beings' (<em>mē ginesthe douloi anthrōpōn</em>) does not mean slave persons should seek legal manumission at any cost, but that believers should not allow human social relations (patron-client dependency, peer pressure, honor-competition) to compromise their fundamental allegiance to Christ. The social criticism targets the Corinthians' unhealthy dependency on human patrons and rhetorical stars.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The third repetition of the 'remain as you are' principle — this time with the added phrase 'with God' (<em>para theō</em>) — adds a theological dimension to the social counsel. The social circumstance in which God's call reached the believer is the space 'with God' — a locative phrase suggesting that whatever the social circumstance, the believer's fundamental location is in relation to God. The Corinthian temptation was to regard spiritual liberation as requiring social liberation; Paul insists that genuine freedom is constituted by the God-relation, not by social status change.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The shift to 'the virgins' (<em>parthenoi</em>, vv. 25-38) addresses a specific Corinthian situation: likely the daughters of household patriarchs (<em>paterfamilias</em>) who are deciding whether to give their daughters in marriage or keep them in the household as celibates. Roman paternal authority (<em>patria potestas</em>) gave the father legal power to arrange or withhold his daughter's marriage; Paul addresses this exercise of paternal authority in an eschatological frame. The 'virgin' category may also include widows who have remained celibate.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The 'present distress' (<em>enestōsa anankē</em>) is disputed: some scholars see a specific local crisis (famine, persecution, social disruption known to the Corinthians); others see an eschatological urgency (the 'time is short' of v. 29). The phrase <em>anankē</em> can mean necessity, compulsion, or distress — used in the Jewish apocalyptic tradition for the tribulation preceding the eschaton (Dan 12:1 LXX; 1 Macc 9:27). Given Paul's imminent eschatological expectation ('the form of this world is passing away', v. 31), the eschatological pressure is probably primary, though a specific local crisis may have intensified it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The marital-binding language (<em>dedesai gynaiki</em>, you are bound to a wife; <em>lelysa apo gynaikos</em>, you are released from a wife) reflects Roman legal concepts of marital obligation. Marriage in Roman law created <em>obligationes</em> (legal obligations) between the parties; dissolution (<em>divortium</em>) formally released those obligations. Paul uses legal binding-releasing language to make his theological point: those who are bound to a marriage should not seek dissolution; those already released need not seek binding again. The legal vocabulary grounds the spiritual principle in concrete social reality.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The concession that marrying is not sinful — 'if you marry, you have not sinned; if a virgin marries, she has not sinned' — is important given the Corinthian context of proto-asceticism. Some in the community apparently regarded marriage as spiritually inferior or even morally problematic. Paul explicitly denies this: marriage is not sin. The 'worldly troubles' (<em>thlipsis tē sarki</em>) of married life are pastoral-practical concerns, not moral-theological objections. The distinction between 'good' (celibacy, Paul's preference) and 'not sinful' (marriage) preserves the full legitimacy of both.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The 'time has grown short' (<em>ho kairos synestalmenos estin</em>) is Paul's eschatological horizon that frames all of ch. 7's counsel. The nautical metaphor of 'compressed/shortened' (<em>synstellō</em>) time suggests time that has been reefed or furled in — the eschatological season is in its final stage. The early church's imminent eschatological expectation (the Lord's return as near; cf. 1 Thess 4:15-17; 1 Cor 15:51) shaped its social counsel: the permanent social arrangements of a stable civilization were less important than the provisional arrangements of a community living toward an imminent end.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The 'as if not' (<em>hōs mē</em>) framework — mourning as if not mourning, rejoicing as if not rejoicing, buying as if not possessing — is an eschatological posture toward worldly engagements. This is not Stoic <em>apatheia</em> (emotional detachment) but what Paul elsewhere calls 'contentment' (<em>autarkeia</em>, Phil 4:11): full engagement with ordinary life without ultimate investment in its outcomes, because the present world-order is passing. Amos 8:10 describes the reversal of feast and mourning in the Day of the Lord; Paul's reversal here is the positive counterpart: present mourning and rejoicing alike are held lightly.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The 'form of this world is passing away' (<em>to schema tou kosmou toutou paragei</em>) uses the word <em>schema</em> (outward form, appearance) rather than <em>morphē</em> (essential form) — the world's passing is its outward ordering, not annihilation. The apocalyptic horizon was widespread in Second Temple Judaism (1 Enoch 1-5; 4 Ezra 7:50; 2 Baruch 74:2): the present world-age (<em>olam hazeh</em>) will give way to the coming age (<em>olam haba</em>). Paul's counsel about marriage, slavery, and social circumstance is shaped entirely by this temporal framework: the social arrangements of the passing age deserve relative, not absolute, investment.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The unmarried person's freedom from worldly anxiety (<em>amerimnos</em>) reflects a specific Greco-Roman social advantage of celibacy: the philosopher who remained celibate was free from the domestic obligations of household management. Epictetus (Discourses 3.22.69-76) explicitly argued that the ideal Cynic philosopher should remain celibate to maintain freedom for philosophical mission. Paul has a similar functional argument but for a different ultimate purpose: the celibate is 'anxious for the things of the Lord', free for total devotion to the divine mission rather than the autonomous philosophical life.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The married man's division of concern — 'how to please the Lord' vs. 'how to please his wife' — describes the practical tension of the ancient household. The Roman household was the primary economic, social, and religious unit; its management was the husband's primary social responsibility. The <em>paterfamilias</em> role involved religious duties (household sacrifices, ancestral cult, civic participation) that could conflict with Christian devotion. The 'division' (<em>memeristai</em>) of the married person's concerns is not moral failure but the structural reality of ancient household obligations.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The unmarried woman's undivided devotion to the Lord parallels the unmarried man's. Roman widows and unmarried women of property could, by the early imperial period, exercise considerable independence in managing their own affairs. Women who had come through the traditional forms of marriage <em>cum manu</em> (under the husband's legal authority) were increasingly replaced by marriages <em>sine manu</em> (without transfer of legal authority), giving Roman women more independence. Widows of the propertied class could choose to remain unmarried and manage their own households — a social reality that Paul's counsel engages.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Paul's stated motivation — 'for your own benefit, not to lay any restraint on you' (<em>pros to hymon sympheron</em>, <em>ouch hina brochos hymin epibalō</em>) — uses the legal image of a noose or snare (<em>brochos</em>): he is not trapping them with a new legal obligation. The ancient Jewish and Stoic traditions had both developed extensive rules about marriage and celibacy; Paul explicitly refuses to add a new restrictive rule. The 'good order' (<em>euschēmōn</em>) and 'undistracted devotion' (<em>euparedron</em>) are positive descriptions of the celibate life's advantages, not negative restrictions on marriage.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The situation of v. 36 — 'if anyone thinks he is acting improperly toward his virgin' — is most naturally read as a father with authority over his unmarried daughter's marriage decision (the <em>paterfamilias</em>). If her age (<em>huperakmos</em> — past the bloom of youth, or the time of strongest desire) makes marriage appropriate, and he is not under constraint, he does well to let her marry. The alternate reading (a betrothed man) is possible but less fits the Roman household context where parental authority over daughters' marriages was the social norm.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The father who 'has decided firmly in his heart, being under no necessity' and 'has determined to keep his virgin as she is' exercises his <em>patria potestas</em> (paternal authority) in favor of celibacy. In Roman law, the <em>paterfamilias</em> had absolute legal authority to arrange or prevent his children's marriages. Paul's acknowledgment of this authority — while making the decision contingent on the daughter's needs and the father's spiritual judgment — reformulates the exercise of Roman paternal authority in terms of spiritual discernment and genuine pastoral concern rather than social ambition.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The summary — 'the one who marries does well; the one who refrains from marriage does better' — completes the comparative structure of the chapter. Both options are legitimate; celibacy has functional advantages in the eschatological situation. The <em>mallon kreitton poiēsei</em> (will do better) is a comparative judgment about advantage in the present situation, not a permanent ontological hierarchy between married and celibate states. The positive framing of celibacy as a charismatic gift (v. 7) rather than a religious requirement maintains both the goodness of marriage and the goodness of celibacy as different callings.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The widow's freedom to remarry 'only in the Lord' (<em>monon en kyriō</em>) — meaning to a fellow believer — reflects the broader Early Christian community's endogamous preference. The Jewish practice of marrying within the community (<em>endogamy</em>) was standard — Tobit and the Deuterocanonical literature emphasize marrying within the people. Paul applies this to the Christian community: the widow is free to choose her husband, but the theological qualification (in the Lord) creates a communal boundary analogous to Jewish endogamy, preventing the social and spiritual complications of mixed marriages addressed earlier in the chapter.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Paul's claim to 'have the Spirit of God' (<em>dokō de kagō pneuma Theou echein</em>) frames his counsel as apostolically authoritative while acknowledging that the celibacy recommendation goes beyond explicit dominical command. The epistemic hedge (<em>dokō</em>, I think/judge) does not undermine the authority claim but accurately signals that he is in the realm of apostolic wisdom rather than quoted Jesus-tradition. The Corinthians who claimed superior spiritual authority were in effect displacing apostolic counsel; Paul asserts that his Spirit-guided advice is as authoritative as any claim to pneumatic inspiration the Corinthians might make.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH8 = {
  "8": {
    "2": "<p>The epistemic critique — 'if anyone thinks he knows something, he does not yet know as he ought to know' — targets the Corinthian <em>gnōsis</em> enthusiasts who believed their theological knowledge licensed unrestricted behavior. The Stoic and Platonic philosophical traditions both prized knowledge (<em>gnōsis</em>, <em>epistēmē</em>) as the basis for virtue; the Corinthian pneumatics may have extended this to claim that genuine spiritual knowledge was self-legitimating for all actions. Paul's counter: the epistemic confidence of the 'knowers' reveals their ignorance, not their wisdom — genuine knowledge begins with awareness of one's own limits.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The relational epistemology — being 'known by God' (<em>egnōstai hyp' autou</em>) as the basis for genuine knowledge — reflects the Jewish covenantal framework where knowledge of God is primarily relational, not propositional. In the OT and Second Temple Judaism, 'to know God' meant to be in faithful covenant relationship (Jer 31:34; Hos 2:20). The passive 'known by him' prior to the human 'knowing' inverts the philosophical epistemology the Corinthians assumed: knowledge of God is not an achievement but a gift — God's prior knowing of the person is the ground of the person's genuine knowing.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theoretical position that idols are nothing (<em>outheis eidōlos en kosmō</em>, an idol has no real existence in the world) reflects the standard Jewish monotheistic polemic against pagan idolatry. The LXX translates <em>elilim</em> (worthless gods) as <em>eidōla</em> (images/idols); Wisdom of Solomon 14:8-11 argues at length that idols are man-made objects with no divine reality. Philo of Alexandria developed philosophical arguments that the gods of Greco-Roman religion were projections of human passions onto cosmic phenomena. The Corinthian 'strong' group correctly understood that idols have no ontological reality — their error was in the social application of this knowledge.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The concession 'even if there are so-called gods in heaven and on earth' acknowledges the phenomenological reality that the Greco-Roman world was saturated with divine beings. The Roman <em>di immortales</em> (immortal gods) were believed to inhabit temples, govern natural forces, and respond to ritual. The Greek theogony (Hesiod's Theogony) populated the cosmos with hundreds of divine beings. Paul's acknowledgment is rhetorically concessive: granting the phenomenological reality of 'many gods and lords' in the polytheistic framework does not concede their ontological status as <em>theos</em> (god) in the Jewish sense.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The 'weak conscience' (<em>asthenēs syneidēsis</em>) group had a pre-conversion association (<em>synētheia</em>) with idol-food that their consciences could not yet separate from their new theological knowledge. The concept of <em>syneidēsis</em> (conscience) as a moral faculty was well-established in Greco-Roman thought (Stoic philosophy; Cicero, De Finibus 2.18.59) and meant roughly the inner awareness or recognition of one's actions as right or wrong. For the weak Corinthians, eating idol-food still registered as participation in actual idolatry because the association between the food and the deity had not been cognitively broken by their theological knowledge.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The principle that food does not 'commend us to God' (<em>brōma de hēmas ou paristēsin tō Theō</em>) reflects the broader NT reorientation of purity from ritual/dietary categories to ethical/relational ones. The Jerusalem decree (Acts 15:29) required abstinence from idol-food among Gentile believers; Paul here applies the more permissive position consistent with his 'in Christ there is no longer Jew or Greek' theology (Gal 3:28). The food is theologically neutral; the issue is what the community does with that neutrality in relation to the weaker sibling.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The 'right' (<em>exousia</em>) the strong Corinthians claimed over idol-food was a form of the freedom-claim that ran through chs. 6-7. In the Greco-Roman context, <em>exousia</em> (authority, right to act) was a property of the socially powerful — those with wealth, status, and education. The strong Corinthians likely were the socially elevated members of the community who had the social connections and obligations to attend temple banquets. Their 'right' to eat had real social dimensions: refusing temple invitations could damage patron-client relationships and social standing.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The scenario of the weak person seeing the strong person eating in an idol's temple (<em>en eidōliō</em>, in the idol's precincts) reflects the social reality of Corinthian temple dining. Archaeological excavations at Corinth have uncovered multiple triclinia (dining rooms) within or adjacent to temple precincts — the Asclepion had eleven such dining rooms. Temple banquets (<em>klinai</em>) were the primary venue for Greco-Roman social networking: civic, professional, and domestic celebrations all involved temple-adjacent meals. The 'weak' believer encountering the 'strong' believer in this setting was confronted with a concrete social dilemma: does Christian fellowship in the body of Christ supersede temple solidarity?</p>",
    "11": "<p>The 'destruction' (<em>apollytai</em>) of the weak person by the strong person's freedom reflects Paul's serious view of communal harm. The vocabulary is eschatological — <em>apollymi</em> in Paul can refer to final perdition (1 Cor 1:18; 2 Cor 2:15; 4:3; 2 Thess 2:10). The one 'for whom Christ died' (<em>di' hon Christos apethanen</em>) — the invocation of Christ's death grounds the seriousness of the harm: to treat the weaker believer's conscience as irrelevant is to treat as nothing the person whom Christ valued enough to die for. The Christological weight overturns the social weight of 'knowledge'.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Sinning against the weak believer is sinning against Christ — the community of believers constitutes Christ's own body (12:12-27), so harm done to any member is harm done to the body and to its head. This is the ecclesiological analog of the Damascus road identification ('I am Jesus whom you are persecuting', Acts 9:5). The striking of the weak person's conscience (<em>typtō... syneidēsin</em>) uses the same tactile-violence verb used for striking a person physically: the injury to conscience is as real and serious as physical assault.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Paul's vow — 'I will never eat meat if it causes my brother to stumble' — is a rhetorical performative of the principle he has been arguing. The <em>eis ton aiōna</em> (forever, to the age) strengthens the resolve: this is not a temporary accommodation but a permanent value-statement. The analogy to Paul's broader missionary practice of accommodation (9:19-23: 'I became all things to all people') is deliberate: the strong person's freedom is not surrendered as a theological concession but freely suspended as a love-expression. Freedom exercised in love requires the willingness to limit oneself for the sake of the other.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '1corinthians')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH5)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH6)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH7)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH8)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1corinthians', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'1 Corinthians mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
